          <mj-text mj-class="pink h2">Performing and Preventing SSL Stripping: A Plain-English Primer</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="https://blog.cloudflare.com/content/images/2017/10/password_not_secure.png"></mj-image>
          <mj-text>Over the past few days we learnt about a new attack that posed a serious weakness in the encryption protocol used to secure all modern Wi-Fi networks. The KRACK Attack effectively allows interception of traffic on wireless networks secured by the WPA2 protocol. Whilst it is possible to backward patch implementations to mitigate this vulnerability, security updates are rarely installed universally.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>It is beyond doubt that it is simply not secure to blindly trust the medium that connects your users to the internet. HTTPS was created to allow HTTP traffic to be transmitted in encrypted form, however the authors of the KRACK Attack presented a video demonstration of how the encryption could be completely stripped away on a popular dating site (despite the website supporting HTTPS). </mj-text>
          <mj-text>This blog post presents a plain-english primer on how HTTPS protection can be stripped and mechanisms for mitigating this.</mj-text>
          <mj-button mj-class="bg-pink" href="https://blog.cloudflare.com/performing-preventing-ssl-stripping-a-plain-english-primer/">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
